\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Entropy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Big-O
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a real or complex valued function and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 be a real valued function, both defined on some unbounded subset of the
 positive real numbers, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is strictly positive for all large enough values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 One writes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=O(g(x))\text{ as }x\to\infty
\]

\end_inset

if and only if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $M,N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\geq N\text{ implies }|f(x)|\leq Mg(x).
\]

\end_inset

This notation can also be used to describe the behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 near some real number 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=O(g(x))\text{ as }x\to a
\]

\end_inset

if and only if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|x-a|<\delta\text{ implies }|f(x)|\leq Mg(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Little-o
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a real or complex valued function and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 be a real valued function, both defined on some unbounded subset of the
 positive real numbers, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is strictly positive for all large enough values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 One writes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=o(g(x))\text{ as }x\to\infty
\]

\end_inset

if and only if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\geq N\text{ implies }|f(x)|\leq\varepsilon g(x).
\]

\end_inset

This notation can also be used to describe the behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 near some real number 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=o(g(x))\text{ as }x\to a
\]

\end_inset

if and only if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|x-a|<\delta\text{ implies }|f(x)|\leq\varepsilon g(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The difference between the earlier definition for the big-O notation and
 the present definition of little-o, is that while the former has to be
 true for 
\emph on
at least one 
\emph default
constant 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the latter must hold 
\emph on
for every 
\emph default
positive constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, however small.
 In this way, little-o notation makes a 
\emph on
stronger statement
\emph default
 than the corresponding big-O notation: every function that is little-o
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is also big-O of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, but not every function that is big-O of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is also little-o of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $2x^{2}=O(x^{2})$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $2x^{2}\neq o(x^{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_body
